article.description: Temeka Johnson had 22 points and seven assists to help LSU beat Mississippi 85-68 Thursday night.
article.headline: LSU's Johnson notches 22 points, seven assists
article.linkText: No. 17 LSU adds to Mississippi's losing streak
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Temeka Johnson isn't really sure what
she'll do next year, but the LSU senior had no doubts about her
role against Mississippi Thursday night.

Playing what could have been her final regular-season home game,
Johnson had 22 points and seven assists to help No. 15 LSU beat
Mississippi 85-68 Thursday night.

Johnson, academically ineligible as a freshman, has not decided
whether to petition the NCAA for an extra year. So, on senior
night, she took her pregame bow, then went to work.

"The senior thing is more for the fans than anything, but I'm
happy the game's over with," Johnson said.

Johnson, third in the nation in assists, was 5-of-10 from the
field and 12-of-15 from the line.

LSU (22-5, 10-3 Southeastern Conference), which clinched a
first-round bye in next week's league tournament with Sunday's
victory over Mississippi State, has won four of its last five
games. Seimone Augustus added 23 points for LSU, which pushed the
sophomore over 1,000 career points. She is the 23rd player in
school history to reach the milestone and the eighth player to do
so in two seasons or less.

"I really wasn't worrying about 1,000 points," Augustus said.
"I didn't even know how many points I had. I just came out and
played."

Scholanda Hoston had 12 for LSU, and the Tigers' other senior,
Doneeka Hodges, had 10.

"I'm glad I was here to see Hodges' and Johnson's last home
game, to make sure they are really leaving," said Mississippi
coach Carol Ross. "They've had incredible careers here. From a
distance it's been fun to watch them. It's not so fun watching them
up close."

Mississippi (15-12, 6-7) is on a four-game skid. Armintie Price
led Ole Miss with 16 points and 12 rebounds, Amber Watts scored 16
and Tywanna Inmon had 10.

LSU stretched its second-half lead to 54-44 on a pair of free
throws by Hoston with 13:38 remaining. Ole Miss came back on a 6-2
run to cut the lead to 56-50 on two free throws by Amber Terrell.

Hodges sank a basket with 14:09 left to put LSU ahead 52-42. The
Tigers did not make another basket until Johnson sank one with 8:54
remaining, but free throws helped them to a 55-52 lead.

"We had to attack to get to the free throw line, so that's what
we did," Hodges said.

LSU shot 44 percent and made 29 of 40 free throws. Mississippi
shot 34 percent and was 22-29 from the foul line. The Tigers
outrebounded Ole Miss 46-37.

The Rebels led for much of the first half, but LSU staged a 19-8
run over the final 7:14 to take a 40-29 lead at the break.
